main event: A radar operator observed a blip indicative of a small object descending and disappearing into ground clutter for 22 minutes on December 5, 1957.
interesting points: The object was estimated to be the size of a quarter., The sighting lasted for a total of 22 minutes., Multiple comments suggest the observed return could be attributed to weather conditions or possibly a weather balloon., The details of the sighting were documented by qualified radar observers., The report includes information about weather conditions during the sighting.
witness description: Major George T. Hanley, RADAR Operator, AcW Squadron; 1st Lt. Buster E. Horton, Senior Director; S/Sgt Mathews, Crew Chief; all from the 663rd ACW Squadron.
